What does it mean to me to be successful?
People use the word "success" a lot, but it doesn't always mean the same thing to everyone. People tell us to "be successful" when we're young, but they don't really say what that means. As we get older, we realize
that many people live very different lives, but many of them still think they are successful. This made me wonder what success really means and if there is a clear definition of it.
To get a better idea of this, I thought about talking to five people of different ages and backgrounds. I also thought about how people from different cultures and times have defined success. After thinking about
all of this, I started to come up with my own definition of success.
I thought of an older man who had worked in a government office for most of his life as the first person I would interview. His job was steady, but it wasn't very interesting. He did the same job for a long time and 
never became very important in his department. He lived a simple life and didn't make much money. He said yes right away when I asked him if he thought he was successful. He thought that success meant being able to 
provide for his family. He didn't have to worry about basic needs because his children were getting an education and his home was stable. He was proud that he had done his job as a parent. This taught me that success 
doesn't always have to be obvious or impressive to other people. Sometimes, it's best to just do what needs to be done without making a fuss.
The second person I thought of was a young man who had started his own business. People on the outside thought his life was going very well. He made a lot of money, worked on interesting projects, and had the freedom
to choose how he spent his time. A lot of people looked up to him. But when he talked about success, he didn't sound sure of himself or at ease. He said that every success only made him feel good for a little while. 
After that, he felt like he had to do something bigger. He thought that success was only temporary and not stable. This made me realize that success based only on what I've done can be tiring and stressful.
The third person was a teacher who was also raising a child by herself. She lived a simple life and didn't make much money. She could have moved up in her career, but she didn't. She said that for her, success meant 
having time and energy to spend with her child. She wanted to be there and not always be tired. She didn't care how far she climbed in her career; she cared about how balanced her life felt. This helped me see that 
doing more doesn't always mean being successful. Sometimes, it means being okay with having less.
The fourth person was a college student whose family was well-off. He could go to good schools and had a lot of chances. His pressure didn't come from money or the need to stay alive, unlike the others. Instead, it 
came from what people thought would happen. He thought that being successful meant showing that he deserved the benefits he had. He was scared of missing out on chances and letting people down. This taught me that 
even people who seem relaxed can be under a lot of stress. He thought that success was linked to guilt and duty.
The fifth person was a small business owner who had failed in business before. He had lost money and had to start over. He gave me a simple answer when I asked him what success meant. He said that success meant not 
giving up when things went wrong. He thought that success meant going on even when it was hard. He thought of success as being able to bounce back, not as getting things done.
After thinking about these different points of view, I started to look at how people used to think about success. In the past, success didn't always mean having money or power. In the past, being successful often
meant living. The main goals were to have enough food, stay healthy, and keep one's family safe. People didn't think they would get rich or famous. They thought they would do their job well.
Many philosophers in the past thought that character was the key to success. People thought that living honestly, staying disciplined, and not going to extremes were signs of a good life. People didn't think that money was the most important thing. In religious societies, success was often linked to doing the right thing. A good life was one that followed certain rules, not one that got rewards.
Success means something very different now. Today, people often judge success by how much money they make, how well-known they are, and how high up they are in the social hierarchy. This change happened when societies became more focused on individuals and competition. People began to compare themselves to others and feel like they had to be different. Success now feels louder and more stressful than it used to.
People from different cultures also have different ideas about what it means to be successful. In a lot of Asian cultures, family is very important to success. It's not just about you doing well; it's also about your parents and other family members. There is a strong emphasis on being responsible and stable. In the West, success is often about being independent and making your own choices. People are urged to chart their own course and determine their own definitions of success.
In some Indigenous cultures, balance is a sign of success. A successful person is someone who gets along well with other people and with nature. People often think that having too much is not needed. This view is more about harmony than growth.
All of these points of view helped me think about what success means to me. Success isn't just one big event or accomplishment for me. It is a slow and steady process. Success means making a life that is stable and easy to handle. It means moving forward without feeling like you're always on the verge of a breakdown.
I think that being in charge of your time and choices is what success means. It's about being able to choose what's important to you instead of always doing what other people want you to do. It also means being able to relax without feeling bad about it and work without feeling angry.
To me, success isn't about making strangers think I'm great. It's about being okay with how my life is going. It should feel like progress even if it's slow. I'd rather move slowly in a direction that makes sense to me than rush toward something that looks good but doesn't feel good.
I also think that you shouldn't have to pretend to be successful. It's not real success if you have to act like someone else or ignore your values to be successful. A life that is successful should feel real. It shouldn't feel weak or like it's going to break at any moment.
I know that my idea of what success is may change as I get older. What seems important now may not be as important later. That's fine. Success doesn't have to be set in stone. It can change as life does.
In the end, success means different things to different people. People see it differently depending on their age, culture, and experience. There is no one right answer. Success isn't about getting to the top for me. It's about not getting lost as you go forward.
That kind of success may not be loud or easy to measure, but it feels real to me, and that's what matters most.
